  "prompt": "How should you treat a bump on your eyeball?",
  "response": "It's really important to **not self-diagnose or self-treat any eye condition.** A bump on your eyeball could be caused by a variety of things, some benign and some potentially serious. Therefore, **you should see an eye doctor (ophthalmologist or optometrist) as soon as possible.**\n\nHere's why, and what to expect:\n\n**Why See an Eye Doctor Immediately:**\n\n*   **Accuracy of Diagnosis:** Only an eye doctor has the specialized equipment and training to properly diagnose the cause of the bump. They can examine the eye thoroughly and rule out serious conditions.\n*   **Avoid Complications:** Delaying treatment for some conditions can lead to permanent vision damage or other complications.\n*   **Different Causes, Different Treatments:** The appropriate treatment depends entirely on the underlying cause. Some bumps may require antibiotics, steroids, or even surgery. Others may simply require observation.\n\n**Potential Causes (not exhaustive, and for informational purposes only \u2013 do not try to diagnose yourself):**\n\n*   **Pinguecula:** A yellowish, raised growth on the conjunctiva (the clear membrane that covers the white part of your eye). It's usually harmless.\n*   **Pterygium:** Similar to a pinguecula, but it grows onto the cornea (the clear front part of your eye). It can affect vision if it grows too far.\n*   **Stye (Hordeolum):** An infected oil gland at the base of your eyelashes. Usually painful and appears as a red bump on the eyelid margin.  While most styes are on the eyelid, they *can* appear close to the eyeball.\n*   **Chalazion:** A blocked oil gland in the eyelid. Usually painless.\n*   **Conjunctivitis (Pinkeye):** Inflammation of the conjunctiva, often caused by infection or allergies. Can cause redness, itching, and discharge.  While it doesn't typically cause a distinct \"bump,\" it can cause swelling of the conjunctiva, which might feel like a bump.\n*   **Cysts:** Small, fluid-filled sacs.\n*   **Corneal Ulcer:** An open sore on the cornea, often caused by infection. Very serious and requires immediate treatment.\n*   **Tumors (Rare):** In rare cases, a bump could be a sign of a tumor.\n\n**What to Expect at the Doctor's Visit:**\n\n*   **Medical History:** The doctor will ask about your medical history, including any previous eye problems.\n*   **Eye Examination:** The doctor will examine your eyes using a slit lamp, which is a special microscope that allows them to see the structures of your eye in detail.\n*   **Possible Tests:** Depending on the doctor's findings, they may order additional tests, such as:\n    *   **Fluorescein Stain:** To look for corneal abrasions or ulcers.\n    *   **Biopsy:** If the doctor suspects a tumor, they may take a small sample of tissue for examination.\n*   **Diagnosis and Treatment Plan:** Based on the examination and any tests, the doctor will diagnose the cause of the bump and recommend the appropriate treatment.\n\n**What NOT to Do:**\n\n*   **Rub or Touch It:** Avoid touching or rubbing the bump, as this can irritate it further or introduce bacteria.\n*   **Try to Pop It:** Never try to pop a bump on your eyeball.\n*   **Use Over-the-Counter Eye Drops Without Consulting a Doctor:** Some eye drops can worsen certain conditions.\n*   **Delay Seeking Medical Attention:** As mentioned before, prompt diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent complications.\n\nIn summary, a bump on your eyeball is a sign that you should see an eye doctor. Don't try to treat it yourself.  Early diagnosis and treatment are key to protecting your vision.\n",
